<TITLE> Bangladesh face Afghanistan in AFC Challenge Cup opener </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 9 (bdnews24.com)  Bangladesh will begin their preliminary round campaign of the AFC Challenge Cup taking on Afghanistan on May 5 at Bishkek Central Stadium in Kyrgyzstan. Hosts Kyrgyzstan will also take on Laos on the opening day at the same venue. Bangladesh, who quit the inaugural AFC Challenge Cup losing to Tajikistan 6-1 in quarterfinal, will play the second match against Laos on May 7 before facing the hosts on May 9. Bangladesh had earlier been placed in Group C along with hosts Kyrgyzstan, Afghanistan and Laos when the 16-team draw ceremony was held at the AFC House in Kuala Lumpur on Jan 15. Sixteen teams, split into four groups, will play the group-phase matches and the top team from each group will join DPR Korea, Turkmenistan, hosts India and Myanmar in the eight-team finals, scheduled for July 30 to August 10. Apart from Kyrgyzstan, Chinese Taipei, Nepal and the Philippines will also host the qualifying rounds. Bangladesh hosted the inaugural AFC Challenge Cup in 2006 where Tajikistan emerged champions defeating Sri Lanka. Group A: Chinese Taipei (hosts), Sri Lanka, Pakistan and Guam Group B: The Philippines (hosts), Tajikistan, Brunei Darussalam and Bhutan Group C: Kyrgyzstan (hosts), Bangladesh, Afghanistan and Laos Group D: Nepal (hosts), Palestine, Cambodia and Macau. 
